events.event_name: UK S&P Global Composite PMI Release
events.description: The release of the UK S&P Global Composite PMI for January 2026, which showed the sharpest expansion in private sector output in 21 months.

facts.fact_text: The UK S&P Global Composite PMI rose to 53.7 in January 2026 from 51.4 in the previous month.

evidences.evidence_text: The UK S&P Global Composite PMI rose to 53.7 in January of 2026 from 51.4 in the previous month

facts.fact_text: The services sector PMI rose to 54 in January 2026.

evidences.evidence_text: supported by both the services sector (54 vs 51.4 in December 2025)

facts.fact_text: Manufacturing output reached a 17-month high of 51.8.

evidences.evidence_text: while that for manufacturers rose markedly to a 17-month high (51.8 vs 50.6)

facts.fact_text: Private sector job counts fell at a faster pace due to rising labor costs.

evidences.evidence_text: rising labor costs drove private sector job counts to fall at a faster pace

facts.fact_text: Input cost inflation slowed compared to the end of 2025.

evidences.evidence_text: On the price front, input cost inflation slowed compared to the end of the previous year

claims.claim_text: Business activity expectations improved for a second straight month.
claims.author: S&P Global

evidences.evidence_text: Looking forward, business activity expectations improved for a second straight month.

evidence.evidence_text: rising labor costs drove private sector job counts to fall at a faster pace
improving demand conditions drove output charges to accelerate
Total new orders received by the private sector rose to a third month in the last four, supported by an improvement in export sales.
